    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey can u help me study for my bio test? i need to understand the different stages of mitosis. can u just like, give me a step by step breakdown of what happens in each phase?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Of course! Mitosis consists of five stages: Prophase, Metaphase, Anaphase, Telophase, and Cytokinesis.\n\nIn Prophase, chromosomes condense and the nuclear envelope breaks down. Spindle fibers form from the centrosomes.\n\nDuring Metaphase, chromosomes align at the cell's equator, attached to spindle fibers from opposite poles.\n\nIn Anaphase, sister chromatids separate and move to opposite poles of the cell, facilitated by the spindle fibers.\n\nTelophase follows, where chromosomes decondense, nucleus re-forms around each set of chromosomes, and spindle fibers disappear.\n\nLastly, Cytokinesis occurs, dividing the cytoplasm and forming two separate daughter cells.",
      "source": "target",
